WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Hope everybody's having a great week and are enjoying the Shiny conference.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Thank you so much to the Appsilon team for putting on this amazing conference and for asking for the Data Science Hangout to be a part of that.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
It's really cool to be included in the conference.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:40.000
If somebody is here from the Hangout and doesn't know what I'm talking about with the Shiny conference, can we share the link in the chat so they know how to join in too?

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:47.000
But I know we have quite a few people here joining the Data Science Hangout for the very first time.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
So thank you all so much for joining us.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
I'm Rachel Dempsey and I lead our pro community at Posit.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.000
So we host this Data Science Hangout every Thursday at the same time, same place.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
So what is it? What's going on here?

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:13.000
This is our open space to chat about data science leadership, questions you're facing, getting to hear about what's going on in the world of data across different industries.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:21.000
And so every week we feature a different data science leader as my co-host to help lead our discussion and answer questions from you all.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
There's no presentations or slides, just all conversation with everybody.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
We're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for everyone.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
And so we always love to hear from everybody, no matter your level of experience or area of work.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
This is a bit different than the Hopin platform that you're in for the Shiny conference.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.000
So I just want to make people aware of that to be a bit careful with unmuting and those things that come with Zoom.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
We'll be watching out for it too, but just wanted to make that clear.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
It is totally, totally OK to just listen in here.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:08.000
But there's also three ways that you can jump in so you can ask questions or provide your own perspective on certain topics by raising your hand here on Zoom.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
If you're not familiar with Zoom, it's in the bar below where it says reactions.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
If you click on that, you can raise your hand.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
You can also put questions in the Zoom chat.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And if you want, just put a little star next to it if you don't want to jump in and read it yourself.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
I'll know that maybe you're in a coffee shop or something and you want me to read it.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And then lastly, we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
And our team here at Posit will share that into the chat in just a second.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
We'll keep posting it in there so that people can find it as well.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
It's great to see all the messages in the chat.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.000
We do share the recordings of each session to the Posit YouTube and our data science hangout site.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
So you can always go back and rewatch or share with a friend.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
But with all of that, thank you so much for joining.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
It's so amazing to see this big group that we have here today.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
And thank you so much, David, for joining us as our featured leader.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:24.000
David Grandjohn is a senior full stack Shiny developer at Novartis and the founder and maintainer of the open source R interface organization where he develops Shiny extensions like BS4- and Shiny Mobile.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:32.000
We also have Bo Wang, senior expert data science at Novartis, who's also joining us in the audience today.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:39.000
He'll be helping with any questions that come up on their data monitoring committees at Novartis as well.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So let me bring you both here to introduce yourselves as well.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:53.000
David, I'd love to have you introduce yourself and maybe share a little bit about your role and also something you like to do outside of work.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Yeah, sure. Hi, everyone. Thanks for having me.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.000
I'm David Grandjohn. I was born in France 32 years ago.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
I'm married. I have one wonderful daughter, a wonderful wife.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:15.000
I'm doing data science at Novartis since four years.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:25.000
My background is about applied mathematics. So I have quite a sort of Swiss knife background where I can do physics.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I can do mathematics, chemistry, a lot of different things and also background in web development.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So when I learned web development, I learned HTML, CSS, PHP and also database on the side.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:53.000
I'm super glad I was able to attend the keynote before from Colleen because I like sport a lot as well.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:01.000
I hate running, but I like cycling a lot and probably for the same reasons as Colleen.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:12.000
So, yeah, at some point, no matter what sport you are doing, if it's making you better, feeling you better, having new ideas,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:20.000
taking some insight of what you are doing, that's just what you have to do.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
We did have a really fun picture of David with his like goggles on,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:30.000
like getting ready to go out for a bike ride that we might have to go up with the recording.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Thank you again, David. Bo, so nice to have you here, too.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.000
It would be great to have you introduce yourself as well.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Thank you. Thank you for having me.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
First of all, I love running and I hate biking.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
I didn't know that about you, David, that you didn't like running.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Maybe we can team up as a relay team in the triathlon or something.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I hated biking when I tried it.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Anyway, so my name is Bo. I work on the same team as David and Novartis.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:12.000
We are data scientists who build tools, pipelines to support our clinical statisticians and other data science functions.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
My background is in biostatistics.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Since I started working in the pharma industry, I've been working on more on the tool development,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
almost like software development side than actual trial analysis.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Although I have been working on supporting data monitoring committees, as Rachel mentioned before,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
and there seems to be a bit of interest in that on that topic in previous meetings.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So that's why I'm here. Outside of work, like I said, I like running.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
I like traveling. I'm actually right now in Memphis, Tennessee, even though I'm normally based in Boston.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
I do not have a wife or a daughter. I do have a dog who I treat as my daughter.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:11.000
She's at my foot, napping. And that's pretty much it. Glad to be here. Thank you.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:18.000
Thank you so much for joining us. And just a quick reminder to everybody, if you're not talking,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.000
if you want to just mute yourself, it will be really helpful.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:33.000
OK, cool. Thank you so much. So I get the pleasure of being able to ask some of the first questions as we wait for questions to come in.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:41.000
But if anybody did just join us after the initial introductions, I wanted to let you know that you can ask questions a few different ways.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So you can put questions into the Zoom chat. You can also raise your hand on on Zoom and I'll call you in.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And we also have a Slido link which we'll share again where you can ask questions anonymously, too.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:06.000
But something I was really excited to start off with asking is, David, I know you think a lot about building great user interfaces.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And I was curious to hear tips you have for all of us in communicating with the business through data visualizations.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:25.000
Yeah, sure. So from I think we started a big project last year, which is around probability of success.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:37.000
And then for this project, we really thought about another way to start our ShinyApp project, especially, you know, from the user interface perspective.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:45.000
So I would say when I joined Novartis at the beginning, most of the time we were, you know, rushing to code.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:53.000
We developed the interface, the app, and then we showed the app to the end user and then they are not happy with the result.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:00.000
We completely changed the process. And with this project, we basically start with wireframing.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:13.000
So we met with the user, we drew the user requirements, we discussed together for one week, two weeks, and then we present some mockups, some wireframing.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So you could basically either use a paper and a pen or you can use more sophisticated tools.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:26.000
I would say it's a bit of pity that most of the good wireframing tools you have to pay.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
We are using Balsamiq, Novartis. You may use it, you may not. It depends if you know.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And then based on that, we spend around, I would say, one month before we can come to an agreement and then we can start to code.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:54.000
So we really developed the application for the end user. That's just from our perspective, you know, so it really satisfies what they want.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Awesome. Thank you. I'm starting to see a lot of questions coming in the chat.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Thanks so much to the Posit team for helping me organize these. But Libby, I see you asked a question. Do you want to jump in?

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:15.000
Yeah, I was just wondering if we could get an overview of some of the big projects that you've been working on at Novartis.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:25.000
I know that Novartis is a pharma company and that it's really big, but being a person outside of the pharma universe, I sometimes don't know what you guys are working on.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:31.000
You want to start on this one, Bo? And then I will take next.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:39.000
Sure. So two of the bigger projects I've been working on, one I've been working on for a couple of years.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Basically, when a clinical trial is being conducted, there are a lot of data analysis on the patient data that we collect from the enrollees.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And for later stage, for later, there are like earlier phases trials in a small amount of patients with lower doses.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And then once the safety established, you move on to later phases with larger number of patients and higher doses for efficacy analysis, for example.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
But the patient safety is always monitored through all the phases.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And for later stage studies, the sponsor in PharmaLingo, the sponsor is a pharmaceutical company that pays for the clinical trial.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:41.000
Anyone inside the sponsor company are not supposed to know the actual treatment of the patients, given if the study is a randomized controlled trial.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:52.000
So we need to hire external partners. Excuse me. Excuse me.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
Thank you.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:13.000
We need to hire we as sponsors have to hire external experts to be unblinded to the actual treatment code and review safety data to make sure that all the patients in the ongoing trial are still safe.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:35.000
So one of the big projects I've been working on in the past couple of years is writing and managing an app, a shiny app that has a JavaScript backend to display some of the safety data in the more user friendly way than, say, 200 pages of PDF.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:45.000
Because the DMC members tend to be very highly regarded, very expensive, their time is very expensive, experts in their field.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
So they have very limited time that they can give us to review the data.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:13:02.000
So having an app as a supplementary tool aids their review of the data with the limited time that they have.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Thank you.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Since I joined Novartis, I've been very lucky regarding all the projects I received.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:25.000
Surprisingly, at the beginning, like during my first month, I was given a project, not about clinical data, but for human resources data.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:31.000
Because you have to imagine, you know, Novartis, it's like 100,000 people working.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And then you have many departments. It's not only clinical, but it's also sales, human resources and many other things.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And basically, we had to develop a tool to better manage the time people spend on projects.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:59.000
And this tool was basically first developed with Shiny, with a lot of databases around just to make sure that data are persistent.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And then later, the tool was improved using other technologies like React.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:13.000
But in the end, yeah, it shows, you know, how you can integrate Shiny in the whole ecosystem.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
And that was a great project.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Then I joined the Probability of Success initiative, which was really a rewarding project because we really had a checklist and tried to respect all possible best practices.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:38.000
This checklist was based on the mistakes we made on other projects.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And then, yeah, we started with the wireframing.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Then we had like a strong CI-CD setup.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
So yeah, I'm responsible of the CI-CD setup of the team.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
So making sure we have...

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:01.000
So we are using GitLab, so we have runners with proper installation, system dependencies, everything.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:09.000
So if you want to do like headless testing for your Shiny apps, you make sure you got the proper installation.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Yeah, so setting up with runners, yeah, how to manage the release, you know, the production release.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:30.000
So this afternoon, we had, during the conference, we had the production release for POS 1.0.0, the first one, which is like one year of work.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
So that's quite a big achievement.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And also, I've been involved...

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
So POS is clinical data, right?

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
It's really to...

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:51.000
I didn't really give the background, but, you know, when you work in pharma, pharma companies, they invest billions into making a treatment.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
It's not just like tens of thousands, it's really billions.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
So you need to make sure what you are going to do is successful at some point.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
You need to know to analyze the market on everything.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And these probability of success tools provide like a data-driven solution to have an improved diagnosis for your probability of success.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And yeah, finally, I've been involved in migration.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:23.000
So it's more like in the server infrastructure.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:27.000
So to migrate from Shiny Server Pro to RStudio Connect.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.000
So initially, yeah, we had Shiny Server Pro and now we have RStudio Connect.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:34.000
So I had to supervise this migration.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:48.000
So essentially talking about thousands of applications and make sure, you know, those applications work correctly on RStudio Connect, POSIT Connect now.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:59.000
So that was quite challenging because all apps were not necessarily following all the best practices, you know, essentially around package dependencies.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
So sometimes you are not able to find, you know, where a package is coming from.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
Yeah, and the application was just not working anymore.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:18.000
So we did a lot of work around RL to set up reproducible environments for many projects, which has a learning curve.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:24.000
But yeah, we are making progress, right?

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
Yeah, and we are also tracking usage on RStudio Connect.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:36.000
So using the API, getting the data from the server to see, you know, how people are using the applications and stuff like that.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:42.000
So that's very, not only people data, that's all data, all possible data.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
That's awesome.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Cool to hear you're using that API too to get those advanced usage metrics.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
I'm seeing a ton of questions coming in here too.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And I want to make sure I get to the ones from the chat too.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:03.000
And so Sep, I see you had asked a question around validation.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.000
Sure.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Thanks, guys, for jumping in and sharing your stories.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:21.000
I know Bo already kind of answered it, but validation is usually, especially in kind of regulated industries, is an arduous task generally.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:29.000
And so I was kind of really interested to see, is that something that you guys have built that required validation to be undertaken?

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
You know, sometimes people have alternatives to that.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So if you could speak to that, I guess, a little bit more, Bo or David, that'd be great.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Yes, I think arduous is the right word to describe the whole process, as I discovered in the past couple of years.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:57.000
I came from my previous experience in my work throughout my graduate school career.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:04.000
I had never encountered the issue of having to validate a piece of software or a piece of application.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Not in the like code review and testing sense, but in the process documentation sense.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:25.000
So it was definitely a learning curve, and we have had a few iterations of processes that are based on software validation.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:41.000
When I say software, you can think of RStudio, the Shiny server, or the RSConnect as a piece of software that we have existing processes written, authored by IT to support.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:50.000
But apparently those processes are a little, there's a little, there's a little too much overhead for a Shiny application.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:20:13.000
So in the past, I would say year and a half, two years, we've been working with our QA colleagues, our IT colleagues, and our colleague who are managing our deployment system or analytical system to kind of communicate both ways.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:28.000
What does quality mean for our QA colleagues? What does quality mean for IT? What does quality mean for business? And try to reach an understanding of how much testing, how much documentation is needed.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:46.000
It's still an ongoing process. We've had a few pilot projects deploy, deploying apps for use in DMC, but there are like exceptions for certain studies that does not apply to other studies.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:21:07.000
So the solution for certain issues don't really translate to long-term solutions that you can write in the process, in like a business process on how to validate a Shiny application. So that's the part that we're still trying to figure out as we incorporate more different types of studies in the program.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
Thanks so much.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
Thank you.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Travis, I see you had a question as well. And I forgot to say, I know there's a lot of people who are here for the first time. So when you jump in and ask your question, if you want to introduce yourself, that would be awesome too.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.000
And I would love to know where you are outside right now.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:44.000
Still San Diego. It's nice here. I saw a few of you here in SoCal. I'm Travis Gerke. I'm also in the CRO space. And I'm a regular jokester here on the Hangout, in the chat usually.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:55.000
Yeah, this is awesome. I did have a question. We also moved away from 800-page PDFs to more HTML-based products. It's been a game changer for our safety monitoring boards. They really like it.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:07.000
But we're not as fancy as you. We're doing more reactable kind of static HTML documents, partly because of the challenge which you just discussed around validation of Shiny servers. So I'm glad Seth asked that question.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:20.000
But one thing that's a gap for us, the feedback that we get from the monitors is still this kind of clunky, maybe they'll write a long email or give us Excel sheets or other things back.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:30.000
What are you thinking about or have you gotten any feedback from users writing your app, which seems like a good opportunity in the Shiny environment?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:41.000
I'm trying to understand your question. Are you asking if we have got positive feedback on the format of the Shiny application from the monitors?

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:47.000
No, actually on the data points themselves. So a lot of times they'll look at a patient profile and go, ah, this lab value, are you sure this is right?

00:22:47.000 --> 00:23:00.000
Or, you know, just the usual kinds of, sometimes it's even data quality questions, which are valid because the monitors are often content matter experts, medical experts, and they see things that we as data scientists don't.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:16.000
It would be very convenient if while they're looking at your app, going through what was previously 900 pages of PDFs, if they could say, ooh, like highlight this and kind of submit right through the app and you could kind of get feedback in that format rather than more traditional methods.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:26.000
Oh, I see. No, we haven't incorporated that in our app to accept feedback directly in the app from the DMC members.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:46.000
In fact, the feedback we've received are mostly not directly from DMC members, even in the email chain, because for pivotal studies for later phase studies, we hire an external CRO to interact with the DMC members directly.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:24:00.000
And we normally just get feedback from them because we're not invited to the meetings because we can't risk unblinding, even though the developers are not technically part of the trial team, but we are still part of Novartis business.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:19.000
That's one of the things that's been part of my learning curve also, how many silos are intended in the process of clinical data review just to make sure data is secure.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:33.000
But I'm sure David might have something to say about building the function of feedback into the app interface to make it more user friendly.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:45.000
Yeah, that's a great question from David. Yeah, because I guess I asked my question. I'm in the CRO side. So that feedback loop is something we're in and you're on the sponsor side. So you're right. Interesting silo that we must adhere to, I suppose.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:50.000
Any other thoughts, David?

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:58.000
Yeah, sorry, I probably missed the last part of Trevi's question about the user feedback, right?

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.000
Not sure I followed correctly.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:15.000
You want me to jump in, David? It was about when you all are giving these reports of, you know, like patient profiles, let's say, so what was previously long 900 page listings in PDF form.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:21.000
